WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.160
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and this&nbsp;
is one of our series of foundational talks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:16.410
on mathematics. Today we're going to introduce&nbsp;
the integers, which is an important extension&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:21.540
of the natural numbers, where we include the&nbsp;
negatives of natural numbers as well as zero.

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:28.410
So here are the natural numbers in Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
notation that we're already familiar with: 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.410 --> 00:00:36.090
2, 3, and so on. To get the integers, we&nbsp;
have to first augment with the number 0&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.090 --> 00:00:40.320
and then the negatives of the natural&nbsp;
numbers extending in this direction.

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:47.520
There are a number of different possible ways of&nbsp;
introducing this to young people. One of them is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:53.370
to use points on a line to think of these natural&nbsp;
numbers and the negative numbers as just being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:59.190
points on a line extending both to the right and&nbsp;
to the left. That makes the negative numbers just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.190 --> 00:01:07.110
as natural as the natural numbers. Another way&nbsp;
is to use a financial model where natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.110 --> 00:01:14.160
correspond to assets (that's money, perhaps,&nbsp;
that you own), while negative numbers correspond&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:21.990
to debts (monies that you owe to somebody else).&nbsp;
Yet another kind is a model of temperature, where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.990 --> 00:01:29.880
you can measure 3 degrees or -5 degrees; you have&nbsp;
some scale which is sort of symmetrical about 0.

00:01:29.880 --> 00:01:37.920
We're not going to use either of these models&nbsp;
because we want to start with only the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:43.230
numbers and do everything with respect to those.&nbsp;
But what we are going to need definitely is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:48.780
system in which subtraction always works. That's&nbsp;
the main reason for introducing the integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:54.690
so that not only can we subtract 2 from&nbsp;
4, but we can also subtract 4 from 2.

00:01:54.690 --> 00:02:01.170
We're going to take our clue from what we&nbsp;
did with fractions. The way we introduced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:05.340
fractions to allow us to do division is&nbsp;
going to be a clue to how we introduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:11.850
integers to allow us to always subtract.&nbsp;
So, we want a system where we're not only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.850 --> 00:02:12.720
allowed to take
3&nbsp;

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:13.740
−
5&nbsp;

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:16.819
3−5, but also
5&nbsp;

00:02:16.819 --> 00:02:16.823
−
3&nbsp;

00:02:16.823 --> 00:02:24.000
5−3, and we want a law like this involving&nbsp;
subtraction to work uniformly for all integers&nbsp;

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:24.176
𝑎
a,&nbsp;

00:02:24.176 --> 00:02:24.420
𝑏
b, and&nbsp;

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:24.780
𝑐
c.

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:30.630
So, our definition of an integer is&nbsp;
very parallel to what we did when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:35.430
introduced fractions. An integer&nbsp;
is defined to be an ordered pair&nbsp;

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:35.985
(
𝑚&nbsp;

00:02:35.985 --> 00:02:36.533
,
𝑛&nbsp;

00:02:36.533 --> 00:02:40.470
)
(m,n) of natural numbers written as&nbsp;

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:42.210
𝑚
/&nbsp;

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:42.900
𝑛
m/n with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:49.500
slash going this way, forwards&nbsp;
and down. When we say this, we say&nbsp;

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:50.340
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:54.240
𝑛
n. This expression is an integer.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:59.340
Now, there's an important notion&nbsp;
of equality between two integers&nbsp;

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:01.136
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:03:01.136 --> 00:03:01.824
𝑛
n and&nbsp;

00:03:01.824 --> 00:03:02.820
𝑘
k less&nbsp;

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:08.070
𝑙
l. They are declared to be equal precisely when&nbsp;

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.120
𝑚
+&nbsp;

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:09.960
𝑙
=&nbsp;

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:10.530
𝑘
+&nbsp;

00:03:10.530 --> 00:03:11.520
𝑛
m+l=k+n; when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:16.200
this one plus this one equals this&nbsp;
one plus this. So, for example,&nbsp;

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:17.220
7
7 less&nbsp;

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:22.770
4
4 equals&nbsp;

00:03:22.770 --> 00:03:27.360
9
9 less&nbsp;

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:27.500
6
6 because&nbsp;

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:27.525
7
+&nbsp;

00:03:27.525 --> 00:03:27.550
6
=&nbsp;

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:27.575
9
+&nbsp;

00:03:27.576 --> 00:03:27.690
4
7+6=9+4.

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:29.820
Another example:&nbsp;

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:31.170
3
3 less&nbsp;

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:32.370
5
5 equals&nbsp;

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:33.060
5
5 less&nbsp;

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:34.230
7
7 because&nbsp;

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:34.860
3
+&nbsp;

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:35.430
7
=&nbsp;

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:36.510
5
+&nbsp;

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:40.050
5
3+7=5+5. Notice that this condition only requires&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:46.500
addition for natural numbers to work. Now,&nbsp;
later on, we're not going to always talk about&nbsp;

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:47.340
7
7 less&nbsp;

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:47.970
4
4, of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.970 --> 00:03:52.320
course. We're just going to end&nbsp;
up identifying this with the usual&nbsp;

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:54.150
3
3, and we're not going to talk about&nbsp;

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:54.780
3
3 less&nbsp;

00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:56.280
5
5 all the time; we're going to identify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.280 --> 00:03:59.070
that with the number we usually call minus
2&nbsp;

00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:06.780
2. Nevertheless, this is the theoretical framework&nbsp;
that pins down what these objects actually are.

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:13.320
So, we have a new type of mathematical object&nbsp;
called an integer, and we denote that new type by&nbsp;

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:14.070
int&nbsp;

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:18.300
int. It's not a natural number, it's&nbsp;
not a fraction, it's an integer.

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:22.290
So, now that we know what an integer&nbsp;
is, we need to define carefully what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:28.890
the operations for integers are. So, here&nbsp;
are the operations. For addition, we have&nbsp;

00:04:28.890 --> 00:04:29.730
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:30.390
𝑛
n and&nbsp;

00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:31.342
𝑘
k less&nbsp;

00:04:31.342 --> 00:04:35.670
𝑙
l. The way we add them is as follows: we take&nbsp;

00:04:35.670 --> 00:04:36.480
𝑚
+&nbsp;

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:39.150
𝑘
m+k, which is another natural number; we take&nbsp;

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:39.765
𝑛
+&nbsp;

00:04:39.765 --> 00:04:41.940
𝑙
n+l, which is another natural number;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:44.070
and then we form the integer
𝑚&nbsp;

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:44.820
+
𝑘&nbsp;

00:04:44.820 --> 00:04:45.690
m+k less
𝑛&nbsp;

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:46.650
+
𝑙&nbsp;

00:04:46.650 --> 00:04:54.900
n+l. It's just the same as what we would do if&nbsp;
these were actual subtractions. So, we're just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.900 --> 00:05:01.080
mimicking the laws that are already existing for&nbsp;
subtraction in defining addition for integers.

00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:05.910
The same goes for multiplication of integers.&nbsp;

00:05:05.910 --> 00:05:07.106
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:05:07.106 --> 00:05:08.310
𝑛
n times&nbsp;

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:09.180
𝑘
k less&nbsp;

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:13.890
𝑙
l. It's a bit more complicated this time. We have&nbsp;

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:14.700
𝑚
×&nbsp;

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:16.350
𝑘
+&nbsp;

00:05:16.350 --> 00:05:17.100
𝑛
×&nbsp;

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:19.860
𝑙
m×k+n×l, all of that less&nbsp;

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:21.600
𝑚
×&nbsp;

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:22.440
𝑙
+&nbsp;

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:23.100
𝑛
×&nbsp;

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.700
𝑘
m×l+n×k. That exactly mimics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:27.990
what would happen if this was
𝑚&nbsp;

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:28.680
−
𝑛&nbsp;

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:29.970
m−n and this was
𝑘&nbsp;

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:30.840
−
𝑙&nbsp;

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:35.460
k−l. In that case, we would have this minus&nbsp;
this. So, we're just again mimicking what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:39.360
happens for ordinary natural numbers when&nbsp;
we take the product of two subtractions.

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:44.100
And now we can define the&nbsp;
inverse operation to addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:48.060
and that turns out to be subtraction,&nbsp;
which is defined directly as follows:&nbsp;

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:49.260
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:50.580
𝑛
n minus&nbsp;

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:51.330
𝑘
k less&nbsp;

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:56.207
𝑙
l is&nbsp;

00:05:56.207 --> 00:05:56.212
𝑚
+&nbsp;

00:05:56.212 --> 00:05:57.300
𝑙
m+l less&nbsp;

00:05:57.300 --> 00:05:58.770
𝑛
+&nbsp;

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.800
𝑘
n+k. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:04.980
the inverse operation, it turns out, to addition.

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:14.310
Now that we have these operations, we can go&nbsp;
about and check all the laws of arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:20.790
that we've already established for natural&nbsp;
numbers. Let me just give you one example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:27.120
Suppose we wanted to verify the law that we&nbsp;
wrote down earlier. So, here's one integer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:29.820
and we are subtracting this&nbsp;
integer minus this integer:&nbsp;

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:31.200
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:32.670
𝑛
n minus the quantity&nbsp;

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:33.900
𝑘
k less&nbsp;

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:34.950
𝑙
l minus&nbsp;

00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:36.000
𝑟
r less&nbsp;

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.460
𝑠
s. Okay, that directly gives us&nbsp;

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:41.090
𝑚
m less&nbsp;

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:43.550
𝑛
n again, and now this thing here is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.550 --> 00:06:45.740
according to this rule here,
𝑘&nbsp;

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:46.940
+
𝑠&nbsp;

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:49.100
k+s less
𝑟&nbsp;

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:49.850
+
𝑙&nbsp;

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:58.010
r+l. And now this integer minus this integer&nbsp;
gives us, again using this definition,&nbsp;

00:06:58.010 --> 00:06:59.990
𝑚
+&nbsp;

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:00.710
𝑟
+&nbsp;

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:03.260
𝑙
m+r+l less&nbsp;

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:04.970
𝑘
+&nbsp;

00:07:04.970 --> 00:07:05.540
𝑠
+&nbsp;

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:10.160
𝑚
k+s+m, and that was the left-hand side.

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:12.020
Now, the right-hand side: if we have
𝑚&nbsp;

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:13.010
+
𝑛&nbsp;

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:13.505
−
𝑘&nbsp;

00:07:13.505 --> 00:07:14.570
m+n−k less
𝑙&nbsp;

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:16.400
+
𝑟&nbsp;

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:17.150
l+r less
𝑠&nbsp;

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:23.840
s, that's equal to this. So, over here, again,&nbsp;
the definition of subtraction of two integers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:29.150
gives us this. Then we add this integer,&nbsp;
and then the rule for addition gives us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:33.590
this one here. So now we have to compare&nbsp;
this expression with this expression,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:41.360
and we see that this is equal to this because&nbsp;
of the ordinary laws for natural numbers, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:47.660
this quantity here is equal to this quantity here.&nbsp;
These are equal, and that establishes the law that&nbsp;

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:48.140
𝑎
−&nbsp;

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:48.650
(
𝑏&nbsp;

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:49.220
−
𝑐&nbsp;

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:49.700
)
=&nbsp;

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:50.180
(
𝑎&nbsp;

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:50.720
−
𝑏&nbsp;

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:51.470
)
+&nbsp;

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:52.760
𝑐
a−(b−c)=(a−b)+c. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:55.010
a law of balance for all integers.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:04.340
One of the big advantages in doing this this&nbsp;
way, as opposed to introducing negative numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.340 --> 00:08:11.390
as the opposites of the natural numbers,&nbsp;
is that the proofs of this law and all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:18.200
other laws become much more uniform. If you&nbsp;
try to prove the laws using natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:23.570
and natural numbers simultaneously, then you&nbsp;
have to subdivide all the proofs into many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:29.090
different cases. This is usually never done&nbsp;
because people always cheat when it comes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:33.320
to establishing the basics of arithmetic, but&nbsp;
if you were to do things correctly, you would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:37.430
find that you would have a lot of subdivisions&nbsp;
into special cases, and it wouldn't be hard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.430 --> 00:08:41.690
but it would be a lot more work than this&nbsp;
rather more uniform, abstract approach.

00:08:41.690 --> 00:08:47.390
Next time, we're going to introduce the rational&nbsp;
number field, which is what we get when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:56.580
amend it so that we can do division. Then we will&nbsp;
have a closed area in which we can do addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.580 --> 00:09:02.700
subtraction, multiplication, and division all&nbsp;
together simultaneously. That's the rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:07.470
number system, and it's the most important&nbsp;
framework for doing arithmetic in mathematics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:12.690
We're going to introduce that next time. I&nbsp;
hope you'll join me. I'm Norman Wildberger.

